endolymph fluid for the inner ear"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibular system in the inner ear is responsible for maintaining balance and spatial orientation. It consists of the semicircular canals, which detect rotational movements, and the otolith organs (utricle and saccule), which detect linear acceleration and head position relative to gravity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetects horizontal linear acceleration and head tilt\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the utricle. The utricle contains hair cells with stereocilia embedded in a gelatinous matrix containing calcium carbonate crystals called otoliths. When the head moves horizontally or tilts, these otoliths shift position due to gravity or acceleration, bending the stereocilia and triggering neurotransmitter release from the hair cells. This information is then transmitted to the brain to help maintain balance and spatial orientation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetects sound wave vibrations in the inner ear\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of the cochlea, not the utricle. The cochlea contains hair cells that convert sound vibrations into electrical signals that are sent to the brain for interpretation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESenses rotational movements of the head\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of the semicircular canals. The three semicircular canals are oriented in different planes and contain endolymph fluid that moves when the head rotates, stimulating hair cells that detect angular acceleration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitors vertical linear acceleration only\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the function of the saccule, the other otolith organ. While the utricle is more sensitive to horizontal movements, the saccule is more responsive to vertical acceleration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduces endolymph fluid for the inner ear\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as endolymph is primarily produced by the stria vascularis in the cochlea and by dark cells in the vestibular labyrinth, not by the utricle itself.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The utricle contains hair cells that detect linear acceleration and head tilt in the horizontal plane.","Otoliths in the utricle bend stereocilia when the head moves, triggering neurotransmitter release.","The utricle is located in the vestibular system of the inner ear and contributes to balance and spatial orientation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93774"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18750"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93774"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T13:33:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T13:34:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11482"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111699"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"ta